      "artworkDetails": """
Girl with a Pearl Earring is an oil painting by Dutch Golden Age painter Johannes Vermeer, dated around 1665. Over the centuries, the painting has been known by various names, but it became widely recognized by its current title towards the end of the 20th century because of the prominent earring worn by the girl in the portrait. The work has been part of the Mauritshuis collection in The Hague since 1902 and has inspired numerous literary and cinematic adaptations.

The painting is a tronie, a Dutch 17th-century term for a study of a head that was not intended as a formal portrait. It depicts a European girl dressed in "exotic" clothing, including an "oriental" turban and a large, striking earring. The identity of the subject remains unknown; she may have been a real model or a more generalized and mysterious figure, possibly representing a Sibyl or a biblical character. Some have speculated that she was Vermeer's eldest daughter, Maria, but this theory is considered unlikely by many art historians.

The painting is executed in oil on canvas and measures 44.5 cm high by 39 cm wide. It is signed "IVMeer" but not dated, and is estimated to have been painted around 1665.

A restoration in 1994 enhanced the subtle color scheme and the intimacy of the girl's gaze. During this process, it was discovered that the background, now appearing somewhat mottled and dark, was originally a deep enamel-like green created by a thin transparent glaze over a black base. Over time, the organic pigments in the glaze have faded. In 2014, Dutch astrophysicist Vincent Icke suggested that the earring may actually be made of polished tin rather than pearl, based on its reflective qualities, shape, and size.
""",
