      "artworkDetails": """
The Starry Night is an oil-on-canvas painting by the Dutch Post-Impressionist painter Vincent van Gogh, created in June 1889. It depicts the view from the east-facing window of his asylum room at Saint-Rémy-de-Provence just before sunrise, with the addition of an imaginary village. The painting has been in the permanent collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City since 1941 and is regarded as one of the most recognizable and celebrated paintings in Western art.

Van Gogh painted The Starry Night during his stay at the Saint-Paul-de-Mausole asylum, where he admitted himself following a mental health crisis in December 1888. The asylum, housed in a former monastery, allowed Van Gogh access to both a second-story bedroom and a ground-floor studio. During his year-long stay, he produced many notable works, including Irises, a self-portrait, and The Starry Night.

The painting features swirling celestial elements, including Venus, which was visible at the time, and an exaggerated crescent moon. The cypress trees in the foreground are depicted on a larger scale than in Van Gogh's other works, and the village is an imaginary addition based on sketches rather than the actual landscape. Van Gogh's letters suggest he viewed the cypress trees primarily in aesthetic terms.

The Starry Night has inspired a wide range of interpretations, from religious symbolism to reflections of Van Gogh’s emotional state. Some art historians connect the swirling sky to contemporary astronomical discoveries, while others see it as an expression of the artist’s inner turmoil. Van Gogh himself was critical of the painting, referring to it as a "failure" in letters to his brother, Theo.

After Van Gogh's death, the painting passed through several owners before being acquired by the Museum of Modern Art in New York in 1941. Scientific analysis has confirmed Van Gogh’s use of ultramarine and cobalt blue for the sky, with Indian yellow and zinc yellow for the stars and moon. The Starry Night remains a touchstone of modern art and a testament to Van Gogh’s unique vision.
""",
