      "artworkDetails": """
The Persistence of Memory (Catalan: La persistència de la memòria, Spanish: La persistencia de la memoria) is a 1931 painting by Salvador Dalí and one of the most recognizable works of Surrealism. First exhibited at the Julien Levy Gallery in 1932, the painting has been in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) in New York City since 1934. It is widely recognized and frequently referenced in popular culture, and is sometimes called "The Melting Clocks," "The Soft Watches," or "The Melting Watches."

The painting introduced the image of the soft, melting pocket watch, epitomizing Dalí's theory of "softness" and "hardness," which was central to his thinking at the time. The soft watches are often interpreted as a symbol of the relativity of space and time, a Surrealist meditation on the collapse of fixed cosmic order. While some have suggested a connection to Einstein's theory of relativity, Dalí himself said the inspiration came from the surrealist perception of a Camembert cheese melting in the sun.

The year before creating The Persistence of Memory, Dalí developed his "paranoiac-critical method," deliberately inducing hallucinatory states to inspire his art. He famously remarked, "The difference between a madman and me is that I am not mad," highlighting his awareness and control over his creative process.

At the center of the composition is a strange, dreamlike "monster" form, which Dalí used in several works as a kind of self-portrait. The creature, with its closed eye and long eyelashes, appears to be in a dream state, and its ambiguous form is typical of figures that appear in dreams. The clocks may symbolize the passing or persistence of time as experienced in dreams.

The orange watch at the bottom left is covered in ants, a recurring symbol of decay in Dalí's work. A fly sits on another watch, casting a human-like shadow. The painting uses highly realistic techniques to depict imagery more likely to be found in dreams than in waking life.

The rocky landscape in the background represents the tip of Cap de Creus in north-eastern Catalonia, a region that inspired many of Dalí's paintings. The shadow in the foreground is a reference to Puig Pení, a mountain in the same area.
""",
      "image": "images/The_Persistence_of_Memory.jpg"
